'''Myōkenhikoyama Kofun Group''' (明見彦山古墳群) is a group of {{ill|kofun|ja|古墳群|1=Kofun cluster|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Nankoku|ja|南国市|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kōchi Prefecture|ja|高知県|12=draft|12=draft}}, in the Myōken area. It is designated as a municipal historic site by Nankoku City.
Situated at the foot of a hill referred to as "Hikoyama," this kofun group comprises three Kofuns from the late {{ill|Kofun period|ja|古墳時代|12=draft|12=draft}}: No. 1, No. 2, and No. 3 kofun. {{Sfn|Myōkenhikoyama Kofun Group (Heibonsha)|1983}}
== List == === Kofun No. 1 === [[File:Myokenhikoyama-kofun 1-1.JPG|thumb|250px|right|{{center|Entrance to the stone chamber of Kofun No. 1}}]] [[File:Myoken Hikoyama Kofun Group-1, 3D-B.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|Overview of the stone chamber in Kofun No. 1}}]] '''Myōkenhikoyama Kofun No. 1''' ({{Coord|33|34|13.39|N|133|36|57.68|E|region:JP-39_type:landmark|display=inline,title|name=Myōkenhikoyama Kofun No. 1}}) is located to the southwest of the group and is collectively referred to as one of the "Three Great Kofun of Tosa," along with the {{ill|Asakura Kofun|ja|朝倉古墳|12=draft|12=draft}} (in {{ill|Kōchi|ja|高知市|12=draft|12=draft}}, Asakura) and the {{ill|Koren Kofun|ja|小蓮古墳|12=draft|12=draft}} (in Nankoku, Okoyachō Koren). Recent surveys include a mound measurement and stone chamber survey conducted in 2005 (Heisei 17) {{Sfn|Survey of Large Late Kofun in Nankoku|2006|pp=1-4, 5-11, 23-29}}, and an excavation survey in 2010 (Heisei 22). {{Sfn|Maibun Kōchi No. 25|2012|p=7}}
The mound is believed to be a round tumulus with a diameter of 14 meters (possibly a square tumulus with sides of 14 meters). It features a {{ill|yokoana-shiki sekkaku|ja|横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|12=draft|12=draft}} with double-sleeve construction. {{Sfn|Survey of Large Late Kofun in Nankoku|2006|pp=5-11, 23-29}}
The dimensions of the stone chamber are as follows: {{Sfn|Survey of Large Late Kofun in Nankoku|2006|pp=1-4, 5-11, 23-29}}{{Sfn|Maibun Kōchi No. 25|2012|p=7}} * Total chamber length: 8.96 meters * Burial chamber: Length 5.64 meters, width 2.16 meters (rear wall), width 2.14 meters (entrance), height 2.8 meters * Entrance passage: Length 3.32 meters, width 1.20 meters
The chamber has been plundered, but remains of {{ill|Sue pottery|ja|須恵器|1=Sue pottery|12=draft|12=draft}} and jewelry have been discovered. {{Sfn|Maibun Kōchi No. 25|2012|p=7}} The tumulus is estimated to date back to the late 6th to early 7th century. {{Sfn|Maibun Kōchi No. 25|2012|p=7}}
<gallery> Myoken Hikoyama Kofun Group-1, 3D-N.jpg|Stone chamber layout Myoken Hikoyama Kofun Group-1, genshitsu-1.jpg|Main chamber (towards the rear wall) Myoken Hikoyama Kofun Group-1, genshitsu-2.jpg|Main chamber (towards the entrance) Myoken Hikoyama Kofun Group-1, sendou-2.jpg|Entrance passage (towards the opening) Myoken Hikoyama Kofun Group-1, sendou-1.jpg|Entrance passage (towards the main chamber) Myoken Hikoyama Kofun Group-1, entrance.jpg|Entrance </gallery>
=== Kofun No. 2 === '''Myōkenhikoyama Kofun No. 2''' was located east of No. 1 kofun. However, it has since been destroyed and no details remain. It is said to have featured a larger stone chamber than No. 3 kofun, indicating its function as a leader’s tomb. {{Sfn|Myōkenhikoyama Kofun Group (Heibonsha)|1983}}
=== Kofun No. 3 === [[File:Myokenhikoyama-kofun 3-1.JPG|thumb|250px|right|{{center|Entrance to the stone chamber of Kofun No. 3}}]] [[File:Myoken Hikoyama Kofun Group-3, 3D-B.jpg|thumb|250px|right|{{center|Overview of the stone chamber in Kofun No. 3}}]] '''Myōkenhikoyama Kofun No. 3''' ({{Coord|33|34|17.81|N|133|37|1.18|E|region:JP-39_type:landmark|name=Myōkenhikoyama Kofun No. 3}}) is located approximately 200 meters northeast of No. 1 kofun. It is a round tumulus with a diameter of 5 meters and a height of 2.3 meters, featuring a double-sleeve {{ill|yokoana-shiki sekkaku|ja|横穴式石室|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|1=Corridor-Style Stone Chamber|12=draft|12=draft}}. <ref name="Explanation Board">Historical site explanation board.</ref>
The dimensions of the stone chamber are: {{Sfn|Myōkenhikoyama Kofun Group (Heibonsha)|1983}} * Total chamber length: 5.8 meters * Entrance passage length: 1.8 meters
Artifacts such as human bones, Sue pottery, straight swords, daggers, horse fittings, iron sickles, iron plow blades, magatama, and tubular beads were unearthed from within the chamber. <ref name="Explanation Board"/> The tumulus is estimated to have been constructed in the late 6th century. <ref name="Explanation Board"/>
<gallery> Myoken Hikoyama Kofun Group-3, 3D-N.jpg|Stone chamber layout Myoken Hikoyama Kofun Group-3, sekishitsu-1.jpg|Main chamber (towards the rear wall) Myoken Hikoyama Kofun Group-3, sekishitsu-2.jpg|Main chamber (towards the entrance) </gallery>
